                      10    ;*****************************************************************************
                      11    ;
                      12    ;*****************************************************************************
                      13    ;* General alterations made by D. Wulf, 12/1999.                             *
                      14    ;* e-mail: Detlef.Wulf@onlinehome.de                                         *
                      15    ;*****************************************************************************
                      16    ;
                      17    ;  The following general alterations are made to the original source code:
                      18    ;
                      19    ;  - The original source code had 2 files BASIC.SRC and FP52.SRC those have
                      20    ;    been incorporated into this file for easy of assembly.
                      21    ;
                      22    ;  - All absolute and relativ jumps and calls without labels were provided
                      23    ;    with labels.
                      24    ;
                      25    ;  - All machine code in the original source, coded in databytes are replaced
                      26    ;    by the menomics.
                      27    ;
                      28    ;  - One routine in the source was different to the ROM code and is replaced
                      29    ;    by the ROM code.
                      30    ;
                      31    ;  - Some "ORG" statements between BASIC and floating point code are remarked
                      32    ;    out.
                      33    ;
                      34    ;  - To get room for new code the "ego message" had to be disabled.
                      35    ;    (Remarked with "Sorry")
                      36    ;
                      37    ;  - To get more room for new code the "FPROG" command had to be disabled.
                      38    ;    (Remarked with "get room")
                      39    ;
                      40    ;*****************************************************************************
                      41    ;* Bugfixes for MCS-52-BASIC from D. Karmann, 8/1993.                        *
                      42    ;* e-mail: dankarmann@lucent.com                                             *
                      43    ;*****************************************************************************
                      44    ;
                      45    ;  - Corrected Intel bug to allow BASIC autoboot EPROM at 8000H with user
                      46    ;    command extensions to work.
                      47    ;    (Remarked as Karmann 1)
                      48    ;
                      49    ;  - Corrected Intel bug to that discarded the 'F' in any variable ending in
                      50    ;    F, FP, FPR and FPRO and followed by a space.
                      51    ;    (Remarked as Karmann 2)
                      52    ;
                      53    ;*****************************************************************************
                      54    ;* Bugfix and performance for MCS-52-BASIC from                              *
                      55    ;* D. Mudric and Z. Stojsavljevic descipt in                                 *
                      56    ;* Elektor Electronics magazine german issue 3/1992.                         *
                      57    ;*****************************************************************************
                      58    ;
BASICNEU                                                                                                      PAGE 2

                      59    ;  - Modifications to the unprocess a BASIC line routine.
                      60    ;    (Remarked as Elektor 1)
                      61    ;
                      62    ;  - Modifications to the floating point subtraction routine.
                      63    ;    (Remarked as Elektor 2)
                      64    ;
                      65    ;  - HEX to BIN performance improvements.
                      66    ;    (Remarked as Elektor 3)
                      67    ;
                      68    ; The same article describes a fix for the multiplication underflow bug, but
                      69    ; the fixes did not work.
                      70    ;
                      71    ; The multiplicaton underflow bug is now (V1.31) really fixed by D. Wulf!
                      72    ;    (Remarked as Wulf 1)
                      73    ;
                      74    ;*****************************************************************************
                      75    ;* Change UV-EPROM to EEPROM programming from R. Skowronek, 4/1996           *
                      76    ;* e-mail: r.skowronek@kfa-juelich.de                                        *
                      77    ;*****************************************************************************
                      78    ;
                      79    ; This altered section of code writes the ram resident Basic program to
                      80    ; EEPROM just like the ROM resident Basic interpreter writes to UV-EPROMs.
                      81    ; The EEPROM is connected just like a RAM, i.e. it uses /wr on pin 27
                      82    ; and gets it's adresses from the real address lines, i.e. the only
                      83    ; difference from the normal setup is the use of the /wr line instead of
                      84    ; P1.4, which supplies the program pulse for UV-EPROMs. Now MCS-BASIC-52
                      85    ; can be located in externally ROM and is non the less able to programm
                      86    ; EEPROMs!
                      87    ; (Remarked as Skowronek)
                      88    ;
                      89    ; The original code from R. Skowronek didn't support the "PGM" statement
                      90    ; this feature is added by D. Wulf.
                      91    ; Memory is now limited to 32K bytes RAM, because memory tests above it
                      92    ; would change the EEPROM.
                      93    ;
                      94    ;*****************************************************************************
                      95    ;* Change timer 0 from 13 bit to 16 bit counter mode to use XTAL up to 78MHz *
                      96    ;* from D. Wulf 1/2000                                                       *
                      97    ;*****************************************************************************
                      98    ;
                      99    ; The max. value for XTAL is now 78627473 Hz, for use BASIC-52 with
                     100    ; Dallas 80C320 high speed / low power microcontroller (33 MHz).
                     101    ; The defaut crystal value is still 11059200 Hz. You can set it with
                     102    ; XTAL or patch the souce code at
                     103    ;
                     104    ;       17F1H = 11
                     105    ;       17F0H = 05
                     106    ;       17EFH = 92
                     107    ;       17EEH = 00
                     108    ;
                     109    ; with a new crystal value.
                     110    ; (Remarket as Wulf 2)
                     111    ;
                     112    ;*****************************************************************************
                     113    ;* New baudrate detection from D. Wulf 1/2000                                *
                     114    ;*****************************************************************************
                     115    ;
                     116    ; The new baudrate detection uses timer 2 for time measurement in state of
BASICNEU                                                                                                      PAGE 3

                     117    ; the code loop timing. So the Dallas 80C320 and other controllers can be
                     118    ; used. Also at higher clock speeds the baudrate will detect automaticly.
                     119    ; (Remarked as Wulf 3)
                     120    ;
                     121    ;*****************************************************************************
                     122    ;* New processor type detection from D. Wulf 2/2000                          *
                     123    ;*****************************************************************************
                     124    ;
                     125    ; A new reset routine detects the processor type. So BASIC-52 V1.3 can be
                     126    ; used with the following controllers:
                     127    ;
                     128    ; 8032, 87C52#, Dallas 80C320, 80515*#, 80517*#, 80517A#, 80528, 80535*,
                     129    ; 80537*, 80575 or similars.
                     130    ;
                     131    ; - On processor types marked with the "*" only two different autodetect
                     132    ;   baudrates, depending on the crystal are possible.
                     133    ; - The processor types marked with the "#" have internal ROM, so BASIC-52
                     134    ;   V1.3 can be located there, because it is still only 8K bytes long!
                     135    ;
                     136    ; (Remarked as Wulf 4)
                     137    ;
                     138    ;*****************************************************************************
                     139    ;* OPBYTE 43H for POP from H.-J. Boehling 1/2000                             *
                     140    ;* e-mail: H-Boehling@gmx.de                                                 *
                     141    ;*****************************************************************************
                     142    ;
                     143    ; A feature of BASIC-52 is the ability to add up to 16 custom keywords
                     144    ; representing commands or instructions that you define with assembler
                     145    ; routines. For using system routines in your assembler code there are
                     146    ; operation bytes (for more information see Intels "MCS BASIC-52 MANUAL").
                     147    ; In the original souce code is no OPCODE to put a value from argument
                     148    ; stack and store in a variable.
                     149    ; With BASIC-52 V1.3 you can use OPBYTE 43H which does the same than the
                     150    ; "POP" statement.
                     151    ; (Remarked as Boehling 1)
                     152    ;
                     153    ;*****************************************************************************
                     154    ;* Reset millisecond counter on "TIME=" from H.-J. Boehling 2/2000           *
                     155    ;*****************************************************************************
                     156    ;
                     157    ; The command "TIME=0" now zeros the millisecond register so that TIME
                     158    ; returns with zero.
                     159    ; (Remarked as Boehling 2)
                     160    ;
                     161    ;*****************************************************************************
                     162    ;* New command "ERASE" by H.-J. Boehling 2/2000                              *
                     163    ;*****************************************************************************
                     164    ;
                     165    ; To erase an EEPROM (fill 16K byte up to 8000H with 0FFH) the new command
                     166    ; "ERASE" is implemented. It takes 2 min. and 45 sec. to erase the 16K bytes!
                     167    ; (Remarked as Boehling 3)
                     168    ;
                     169    ;*****************************************************************************
                     170    ;* Correct "ASC(x)" bug by D. Wulf 2/2000                                    *
                     171    ;*****************************************************************************
                     172    ;
                     173    ; BASIC-51 V1.1 gives erroneous results for the "ASC(x)" funktion if "x" is
                     174    ; one of the following signs : *, +, -, /, <, =, > or ?.
BASICNEU                                                                                                      PAGE 4

                     175    ; BASIC-51 V1.3 returns the correct values.
                     176    ; (Remarked as Wulf 5)
                     177    ;
